Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome to our 20th Weekly Dose of Optimism. That=E2=80=99=
s 20 straight weeks of optimism dropped into your inbox. Here=E2=80=99s to =
hoping the world gives us the content we need for the next 20!
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6Athletic Greens [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/7e640c57-c94b-4df3-989a-b263932d3e12?r=3D9p0gt ]
We convinced the team over at Athletic Greens to give us an exclusive offer=
 for our audience (legitimately, not the way people normally say that): 10 =
Free Travel Packs [ https://substack.com/redirect/7e640c57-c94b-4df3-989a-b=
263932d3e12?r=3D9p0gt ] when you subscribe.
At this point you probably are familiar with Athletic Greens =E2=80=94 it=
=E2=80=99s the easiest way to get your daily nutrients. I start every morni=
ng with a special AG1 concoction. I started taking it when my brother Dan g=
ifted it to me two Christmases ago=E2=80=A6which leads me to my next point:=
 it makes a great gift. So whether you want to boost your morning routine o=
r give a standout gift this holiday season, check out our exclusive offer b=
elow:
(1) Lifting 100 million out of poverty by 2025 still possible, despite rece=
ssion threat [ https://substack.com/redirect/44f8c321-0bae-4bd9-9957-d8b349=
6af174?r=3D9p0gt ]
From The United Nations
In India, some=C2=A0415 million people left multidimensional poverty in a 1=
5-year period=C2=A0- a historic change - and data gathered before the COVID=
-19 pandemic show that=C2=A072 countries had significantly reduced poverty=
=C2=A0over recent years.
This report from the UN was released a few weeks ago, but the staggering st=
at of 415 million people in India being lifted out of poverty over the past=
 15 years is still making the rounds on the internet. 415 million people =
=E2=80=94 holy shit! That means that over the past 15 years, more than one =
United States=E2=80=99 worth of people have seen a meaningful, measurable q=
uality of life improvement just in India. There is much work to be done, bo=
th in India and the rest of the world. In India, for example, 10% of the po=
pulation =E2=80=94 or about 140 million people =E2=80=94 still live in pove=
rty. But despite Covid-induced setbacks, the UN believes it=E2=80=99s well =
on its way to lifting an additional 100 million people out of poverty by 20=
25, due to a combination of integrated poverty reduction strategies such as=
 sanitation, decarbonization, and nutrition programs.
(2) What Policies Promote Abundance? [ https://substack.com/redirect/42b781=
f0-22d7-4c7d-b881-bc8120e8915b?r=3D9p0gt ]
From The Center for Growth & Opportunity
There is reason to be deeply optimistic about the future of the US economy.=
 Yes, at the moment we face many headwinds=E2=80=94shortages in labor,=C2=
=A0housing,=C2=A0medicine, gasoline, fertilizer,=C2=A0baby formula, and mic=
roprocessors continue to linger. At the same time, the rapid development of=
 vaccines, the resiliency of digital technology and communications, and our=
 history of innovation all point to a bright future.=C2=A0
The lesson of these shortages and our post-COVID world is simple: We need t=
o build. We need abundance. With the right policies in place, America can, =
and will, succeed.
Abundance means greater economic growth, higher quality of life, greater en=
vironmental sustainability=E2=80=94all at cheaper prices. A future of abund=
ance is not guaranteed. It is a place for conditional optimism. Meaning tha=
t if Congress takes the right steps in important areas, then abundance is w=
ithin reach.
At Not Boring, we=E2=80=99ve written extensively on the Abundance Agenda [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/b513343b-51e4-4e66-be6e-0b7e5771310d?r=3D9p0g=
t ] =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s the idea that we can (and need to) increase acce=
ssibility to essential goods by increasing supply, which means more (and ch=
eaper) energy, production, and infrastructure. But how do we make it happen=
? It will require deep cooperation between government, industry, and academ=
ia. The government=E2=80=99s role is to reduce unnecessary red tape and pro=
vide funding, academia provides the foundational R&D, and industry commerci=
alizes and scales.=20
The Center for Growth & Opportunity at Utah State University [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/ce887fc2-65ec-4709-b13b-4a74d78a321b?r=3D9p0gt ] is one o=
f the leading research centers publicly advocating for the Abundance Agenda=
, and it recently published a list of abundance recommendations to Congress=
=2E=20
The authors group the recommendations into three buckets:=20
Technology: increase competition, improve the FDA, broadband access for all=
, remove barriers to transportation innovation (give me my flying car!), an=
d expand employment flexibility
Environmental Stewardship: faster clean energy with procedural tweaks, resi=
lient grids, proactive wildfire management, and land conservation
Immigration: expand immigration to boost entrepreneurship and build a bette=
r pathway for skilled immigration=20
The future is bright if the government, academia, and industry all pull in =
the same direction. The full piece [ https://substack.com/redirect/42b781f0=
-22d7-4c7d-b881-bc8120e8915b?r=3D9p0gt ] is well worth the read for more de=
tail on all of the above.
(3) The promise of cultivated meat [ https://substack.com/redirect/dbdca225=
-ff14-4734-acf6-d56476b15b3b?r=3D9p0gt ]
Joshua March [ https://substack.com/redirect/3e9b1abc-eed8-40e3-8a8c-80fbd8=
888c2f?r=3D9p0gt ] for Noahpinion
Conventional meat has a dirty little secret: it is one of the biggest contr=
ibutors to climate change. According to the UN Food & Agriculture Organizat=
ion, emissions from livestock account for a startling 14.5% [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/ccd3a10f-96fa-49ac-ae65-cc13949e25f6?r=3D9p0gt ] of all an=
thropogenic greenhouse gas emissions (compared to just 3.5% for aviation [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/b7836927-0c38-4ab0-8ac6-07760cb76f03?r=3D9p0g=
t ]). And while energy production is rapidly making a transition to renewab=
les, conventional meat consumption is only increasing (as the world=E2=80=
=99s population gets wealthier, people eat more meat)=E2=80=94and with it, =
the associated greenhouse gas emissions. Even if all energy production swit=
ched to 100% renewable power today the emissions from animal agriculture al=
one would still push us past the 2 degree celsius warming threshold [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/8d5758b6-b505-42a8-8185-c5b8365a0464?r=3D9p0gt ].
People like meat. As more people are lifted out of poverty, more people wil=
l want to eat meat. Whether that =E2=80=9Cmeat=E2=80=9D is going to come fr=
om animals, plants, or a lab remains to be seen, but the planet is in troub=
le if it all needs to come from animals.=20
=E2=80=9CCultivated meat=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 a methodology first commerciali=
zed by Memphis Foods (now Upside Foods) in which meat is cultivated from an=
imal cells in bioreactors, is one promising source of that meat. The proble=
m, historically, with meat alternatives is that the product either doesn=E2=
=80=99t actually taste like meat (plant), doesn=E2=80=99t have the structur=
e of meat we=E2=80=99re used to eating (cultivated), or is too expensive to=
 produce (both). March, the president of SciFi Foods [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/7500b635-72f4-4f72-8d47-827042934ee4?r=3D9p0gt ], lays out an alt=
ernative methodology that is meant to solve each of these problems: blended=
 meat.=20
Blended meat combines the flavor benefits of cultivated meat and the struct=
ural characteristics of plant-based meats. There are definitely still chall=
enges to this approach =E2=80=94 cost, mass appeal, etc. =E2=80=94 but more=
 (clean, healthy, non-animal-harming) meat is an agenda we can get behind.
(4) Pulses to Their Brains and 2 Women=E2=80=99s Binge Eating Went Away [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/09a6d2bd-3010-403c-9058-6eca8af5f03e?r=3D9p0gt=
 ]
Gina Kolata [ https://substack.com/redirect/261f55b1-efae-4278-826d-7d8191d=
bba57?r=3D9p0gt ] for The New York Times
The pilot study [ https://substack.com/redirect/7073331c-6f8a-4ed2-a32f-594=
de74f612a?r=3D9p0gt ], funded by the National Institutes of Health and publ=
ished earlier this year in the journal Nature Medicine, involves two women =
and will be expanded in a few months to include four more people living wit=
h binge eating disorder who regained the weight they lost after bariatric s=
urgery. Before the treatment can be approved by the Food and Drug Administr=
ation, researchers will need to rigorously test the method in at least 100 =
people in multiple medical centers. Such a study would take several years t=
o complete.
Obesity is frustrating. It=E2=80=99s a seemingly very solvable problem, bot=
h at the individual level and the population level. Eat less! Eat healthier=
! Burn more calories than you are putting in your body! But it=E2=80=99s ob=
viously not so easy: over 40% of the U.S. population is obese.=20
Obesity, simply speaking, is caused by eating too much and moving too littl=
e. Why people eat too much or move too little can be explained by dozens of=
 different factors including: food costs and accessibility, lifestyle choic=
es, medical conditions, and more. About 3% of the population suffers from a=
n eating disorder called =E2=80=9Cbinge eating.=E2=80=9D A small-scale stud=
y is using deep-brain stimulation =E2=80=94 a methodology generally used to=
 treat Parkinson=E2=80=99s patients =E2=80=94  to curb the mental (and phys=
ical) urge to binge eat. While only two women participated in the study, th=
ey both reported no longer feeling the irresistible urge to binge. Scaling =
the treatment to the general population could take years, but the findings =
offer an interesting view into the mind-body connection and an opportunity =
to curb the obesity epidemic.=20
(5) Online internal speech decoding from single neurons in a human particip=
ant [ https://substack.com/redirect/d60e5f2d-52dc-4c36-815f-7cf4b482066e?r=
=3D9p0gt ]
From Sarah Wandelt [ https://substack.com/redirect/6cf704c0-23d5-4f2f-972b-=
8d9c0aa43eb0?r=3D9p0gt ] et al
Speech brain-machine interfaces (BMI=E2=80=99s) translate brain signals int=
o words or audio outputs, enabling communication for people having lost the=
ir speech abilities due to diseases or injury.
We=E2=80=99re one step closer to the future imagined by Tim Urban in The Br=
ain=E2=80=99s Magical Future [ https://substack.com/redirect/9c0bc1b0-0e64-=
4936-bb23-dadbf254551d?r=3D9p0gt ]. A team at Caltech has devised a way to =
translate internal words into speech. Think a word in your head =E2=80=94 n=
ow imagine a machine speaking that word out loud=E2=80=A6that=E2=80=99s kin=
d of how it works. Like Urban imagined, this type of BMI technology will li=
kely help people suffering from diseases or injuries first. Imagine an ALS =
patient =E2=80=94 she has full mental faculties but no ability to speak =E2=
=80=94 using the BMI to communicate her needs to a nurse. And while initial=
 use cases will likely be limited to medical treatment, you can imagine a w=
orld in which our brains are communicating synchronously with a variety of =
different systems that give us augmented superpowers.
BONUS 1: Thinking Together [ https://substack.com/redirect/e734c3ed-a910-41=
f9-a61a-3519881d658e?r=3D9p0gt ]
Gordon Brander=20
While analyzing a global history databank spanning 10,000 years, Shin, et a=
l found a disconcerting pattern. Civilizations scale until they are overwhe=
lmed by the information environment they create. This is The Information Sc=
aling Threshold.
It=E2=80=99s been a brutal week for crypto. FTX, which sponsored this newsl=
etter and podcast and seemed to be one of the safest companies in the space=
, collapsed after using customer deposits to prop up its sister hedge fund,=
 Alameda. There=E2=80=99s nothing good about the situation; it was fraud. A=
 lot of people are reflecting on whether and why they should care about cry=
pto anymore after another high-profile ponzi.=20
For me, it=E2=80=99s projects like Noosphere [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/80809c0c-f90f-45ec-900c-c6adc3d5f45f?r=3D9p0gt ], a protocol for thought =
that aims to help people think together in order to solve the world=E2=80=
=99s most pressing and complex challenges.=20
In this piece, Gordon makes the case that we've created more information th=
an we can make sense of with our current tools, and that the future of civi=
lization depends on our ability to get our arms around our information envi=
ronment. To pull it off, we=E2=80=99ll need open protocols that can respond=
 to the complexity of that environment, and tools that merge human and AI c=
apabilities to think better together. I=E2=80=99m excited to see what Noosp=
here pulls off, and to use the product.=20
BONUS 2: Anton Teaches Packy AI [ https://substack.com/redirect/0d46bd7c-84=
a3-4324-993f-a1649d21497d?r=3D9p0gt ]
On Monday, we dropped the first episode of Anton Teaches Packy AI on Youtub=
e. The series is meant to demystify AI for curious, but not overly technica=
l folks=E2=80=A6like me! As of writing, we already have 420 (nice) subscrib=
ers to our Youtube channel and we=E2=80=99re looking to grow our following =
and put out more video content. The channel will be a combination of Anton =
Teaches Packy AI, Not Boring Founders video podcasts, and presumably other =
content best suited for video. If that=E2=80=99s something you=E2=80=99re i=
nterested in, SMASH THE SUBSCRIBE BUTTON.
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. If you enjoyed this edition, we=E2=80=99d=
 really appreciate if you shared it with a friend, family member or colleag=
ue.
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox 9am EST on Monday morning. Enjoy the we=
ekend.
Packy

